AB  - Projections of stones, ashfalls, tremors and ground deformations are among the factors which caused a great deal of damage to the plants. In areas where the burying was not too significant, herbaceous species with underground storage organs and most of trees survived. The grasses Polygonum sachalinense and Petasites japonicus, the horsetail Equisetum arvense, and the trees Populus maximowiczii, Acer mono and Ulmus davidiana survived best. In some areas thickly covered with ash and pumice, primary invasion started quickly (probably in 1979-80). The herbaceous pioneer plants originated mostly from proximate surviving mother-plants. Seeds were transported by wind and also by water along the rills and gullies. The pioneer trees originated almost exclusively from light anemochorous seeds coming from relatively undisturbed forest outside the caldera. Salicaceae are the best represented among the pioneer trees. Mosses invaded the ash-pumice desert along with the phanerogams. In habitats such as the fumarolic zones, only mosses and blue algae are found. Plant recovery and invasion do not seem to be limited by disseminule supply or the low nutrient value of the new volcanic deposit, but by intensive geomorphic processes such as slope-wash mud and debris flows.-from Author
