TI  - Talus and pediment flatirons - indicators of climatic change on scarp slopes on the Colorado Plateau, USA
PY  - 1996
T2  - Zeitschrift fur Geomorphologie, Supplementband
VL  - 103
SP  - 135
EP  - 158
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-0030455446&partnerID=40&md5=4973e05f81d96702cb906303259651f7
AD  - Institut für Geographie, Martin-Luther-Univ. Halle-Wittenberg, D-06108 Halle, Domstr. 5, Germany
AB  - Talus and pediment flatirons are slope form assemblages on dryland cuesta scarps. They have triangular to trapezoidal groundplans with their tops directed towards the scarp. During the cold(humid) periods the present backslopes of both the talus and pediment flatirons were parts of a continuous debris slope system. They were detached from the scarp by dissection, slope steepening and cliff retreat during the subsequent dry phase. Relaxation times are longer and thresholds for formative change are higher for slopes than for rivers and valley floors. Thus only major climatic changes are documented in slope form assemblages. On the Colorado Plateau the climato-cyclic flatirons are found on concave lower scarp slopes developed in the soft homogeneous Mancos Shale. Most of them have formed on the slopes of the Book Cliffs, fewer in the Mesa Verde area. Morphodynamic change on the Mancos Shale slopes was primarily caused by the considerable vertical dislocations of the vegetation belts during the late Pleistocene. The establishment of woodland vegetation in the humid phase led to slope stabilization, and the migration of the desert shrub zone into the lower slope and the foreland of the scarps gave the decisive impulse for dissection. The footslope of the Book Cliffs lies in this environmentally sensitive migration belt. Here multi-level sequences of talus and pediment flatirons have been preserved, each flatiron backslope documenting the latest stage of a cold(humid) period. The distance of the youngest flatiron to the present scarp slope is indicative of Holocene scarp retreat. A rough estimate of 2 m/ 1000 a was obtained in the calculation of the rate of retreat. The inter-flatiron erosional gaps are the product of scarp recession during the dissection-controlled dry phase (interpluvial) and the subsequent debris flow-controlled humid phase (pluvial). The distance between two successive flatiron generations can be used for estimating scarp retreat in an interpluvial / pluvial cycle. For the cycle between latest Illinoian and latest Wisconsin an average rate of retreat of about 3.5m/ 1000 a was calculated for the Book Cliffs. This late Pleistocene rate is more reliable because a longer timespan is covered in the derivation. The cyclic flatirons are only found in those parts of the Colorado Plateau where presently the annual precipitation ranges between more than 200 and less than 350-400 mm, with most flatirons having developed in the lower part of this precipitation interval. Caution is needed in spatially extrapolating climatic thresholds, which separate conditions favourable for debris slope formation or slope dissection. They are only valid for a specific set of litholological, structural and biotic conditions. The clayey and in many places alkaline Mancos Shale with its low soil moisture availability is extremely unfavourable for plant growth. The lower treeline (lower limit of the pinyon-juniper woodland) lies in higher elevations than in the surrounding terrain. Thus cyclic flatirons on the Colorado Plateau have also originated on scarp slopes with relatively moist climatic conditions as demonstrated for parts of the Mesa Verde.
